"One time, however, we were near
quarrelling. He said the pleasantest manner
of spending a hot July day was lying from
morning till evening on a bank of heath in
the middle of the moors, with the bees hum-
ming dreamily about among the bloom, and
the larks singing high up over head, and the
blue sky, and bright sun shining steadily and
cloudlessly. That was his most perfect idea
of heaven's happiness--mine was rocking in a
rustling green tree, with a west wind blowing,
and bright, white clouds flitting rapidly
above; and not only larks, but throstles, and
blackbirds, and linnets, and cuckoos pouring
out music on every side, and the moors seen at
a distance, broken into cool dusky dells; but
close by great swells of long grass undulating
in waves to the breeze; and woods and sound-
ing water, and the whole world awake and
